com.milk.uberchat.spacebar
Class SBInteractor

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.milk.uberchat.spacebar.SBInteractor
class SBInteractor
extends java.lang.Object

This class does all the interaction with a SpaceBar server. It takes input in the form of filtered messages (filtered through a SBInputFilter) and explicit calls to do stuff. It sends stuff back to the server depending on what it's told to do, and messages etc. along to a SBSystem depending on what gets received from the connection.

Author:
Dan Bornstein, danfuzz@milk.com
, Copyright 1998 Dan Bornstein, all rights reserved.

receiveSystemMessage

private MessageEvent receiveSystemMessage()
This will receive a message from the input, handling everything appropriately, except for non-speech MessageEvents, which it returns without any processing. Handling appropriately includes adding Runnables to the command queue and telling the system about speech messages. If a message is received and processed that wasn't a non-speech MessageEvent, this method returns null.

Returns:
null-ok; the unprocessed MessageEvent, if any

receiveMessage

private void receiveMessage()
This will receive a message from the input and handle it appropriately. This does everything that receiveSystemMessage does, plus it will set myLastPrompt when prompts are received, and it will send all other chat messages to the main system object.

expectPrompt

private void expectPrompt(java.lang.String type)
This will receive and handle messages until a prompt is received; it then makes sure the prompt is the one that's expected. If it's not, then it throws an exception, otherwise it just returns normally.

Parameters:
type - the prompt type

ignoreUntilPrompt

private void ignoreUntilPrompt(java.lang.String type)
This is like expectPrompt, except system messages are silently eaten. This allows, e.g., hiding "informative instructions" about some of the more esoteric commands.

Parameters:
type - the prompt type

gotPrompt

private boolean gotPrompt(int count,
                          java.lang.String type)
This expects the possibility of the given prompt. If the prompt is received within the given number of lines, it returns true. If only non-prompt messages are received, it returns false and sends along the messages for normal processing. If a prompt other than the expected one is received, it immediately returns false, leaving the prompt in the myLastPrompt variable.

Parameters:
count - the count of lines to try
type - the prompt type

promptThenType

private void promptThenType(java.lang.String type,
                            java.lang.String line)
This expects either the given prompt or a SYSTEM_PRIVATE line. If the prompt is received, it types the given line. If a SYSTEM_PRIVATE is received, it just sends that back to the system. (It was presumably an abort type message such as "flooby not logged in.").

Parameters:
type - the prompt type
line - the line to send

line - hte line to ignore

typeLine

private void typeLine(java.lang.String line)
Send the given string to the host system as typing. In particular, expect it to be echoed back out, and if it doesn't end with newline, expect a newline too.

Parameters:
line - the line to send

gatherResponse

private java.lang.String[] gatherResponse()
Gather a response from the host. Since SpaceBar sucks, we cheesily use an invalid command as the delimiter to know that the response is done.

Returns:
the array of lines received as a response
